ce:section.ce:para:
With the aim of delivering sildenafil in a controlled fashion, we functionalized CDs, obtained using a protocol reported elsewhere (Mauro et al., 2022) (Fig. S1), with β-cyclodextrin at the surface. A few cyclodextrin-CDs conjugates have been reported mainly for sensing applications so far. For instance, Jorge Espina-Casado et al. have developed CDs randomly modified with β-cyclodextrin, demonstrating that they can decrease cell viability inducing alterations in the cell cycle in cancer cells and can increase the fluorescence quantum yield in cancer cells both in vitro and in vivo (Espina-Casado et al., 2021). Angelina Cayuela et al. have obtained CDs functionalized with carboxymethyl-β-cyclodextrin via amide bonds, for the direct determination of water-soluble C60 fullerene (Cayuela et al., 2016). Unfortunately, because of the high heterogeneity of the β-cyclodextrin monomer due to multifunctionalities of hydroxyl groups, it is unlikely that available strategies would guarantee high homogeneity of the conjugate samples, desirable for medical and pharmaceutical applications. We try to circumvent these drawbacks using a click-chemistry protocol using monofunctional β-cyclodextrin building blocks. Briefly, crystalline and highly homogeneous CDs of roughly 5.1 ± 0.3 nm in diameter, endowed with multicolor emission and bearing several carboxylic groups at the surface (Fig. S2), were prepared and coupled with discrete amino-PEG4-alkyne chains by amide coupling, using EDC and NHS as activating agents (Fig. 1
                        ). The addition of alkyne functions at the CDs surface and the use of fairly low molecular weight PEG spacer provided functional groups suitable for the Huisgen cycloaddition of monofunctional 6-azide-β-cyclodextrin, giving rise to nanosystems which consist of a CD core decorated with β-cyclodextrin at the surface. The FTIR spectrum reported in Fig. 2
                        a displays typical vibrations of aliphatic protons of PEG chains at 2950 cm−1, coupled with the I and II amide bands at 1560 and 1480 cm−1, respectively. There are also asymmetric and symmetric vibrations of C-O-C PEG bonds at 1100––1200 cm−1, which corroborate the feasibility of the amide coupling with amino-PEG4-alkyne at CDs surface.
